It's nice however there is room for improvement.

Be careful with your comma placement as it directs how words flow. An example is:
>She took off her glasses, folding them neatly as she put them back in the case on her desk, and stood up.
The last comma interrupts the flow.

Also word use could be improved with the word 'prick' seeming out of place.

But overall it was nice, short and smutty piece.

>>33864931
>I was thinking doing chap 1 as if it was a handheld almanac as if the main character is reading it, but ideas welcome
I'm going to save you pain and tell you not to do that if you're still learning and spreading your wings. Your opening's goal is to immerse the reader so they're hooked, an info dump doesn't do that. It's much safer to start with something happening so readers have an interest in either the events, a character the story will follow, or both. For example, there's a reason a lot of heroic narratives start with the idea of a simple farm boy or country nobody aside from humble beginnings begetting great things. It gives an easy to understand starting place for the reader that you can naturally expand on. You don't have to do it that way. Giving a strong scene impression with only one or two lines can give a strong starting point to jump into some events or action.

Of course this is assuming you're writing prose. Shorter greentext allows for some front loading, but if you end up writing half a dozen or more lines setting out backstory you might want to reconsider. A common piece of storytelling advice is to make sure you're writing the interesting or necessary parts of the story. In the very beginning, the most necessary thing is to get the reader invested, not give them a geography or history lesson.

Anonymous Thu 05 Nov 2020 07:23:16 No.33865323 Report
Quoted By: >>33865514 >>33876317
>>33864931
There’s a danger in slapping the reader with exposition, no matter how you present it in story. Firstly because as interesting as some may find the world and setting, people read for the characters and their action, with the setting as the spice. Secondly because as much as you can tell people are the ins and outs of the setting there will always be something more to cover so you’ll never end up covering everything.
You’re better off letting details appear organically through the story. The introduction of an element (like magic, technology, presence of anthros themselves or whatever) can be covered by a character’s reaction, and therefore you tell the reader whether that element is normal, totally new, uncommon but understood, etc. From that reaction the reader gains their guidepost for other elements.

These elements can be discussed shortly after the event to give details; with magic as an example, a casual discussion on how a type of magic is a pain in the ass because lowlife’s always use it, or exclaim about how a character has heard about this type of magic but never seen it in person, them have another character have an anecdote about something they’ve seen or read as the characters crack wise. Or talking about how someone’s never been spooked or even believed in magic, and that’s what a character swear they saw so then a debate forms about who believes them.

You’re building the world, introducing and establishing characters by their attitudes and mannerisms and advancing the plot at the same time.

Anonymous Thu 05 Nov 2020 07:44:28 No.33865514 Report
Quoted By: >>33876317
>>33865183
Quddite here. Using >>33865323 as an example, front loading can work IFF you adjust it to fit the format you're writing in. Greentext? Spoon-feed a little information about it in the form of an in-character foreword. Long, drawn-out story? Bit tougher, but if you can put it in without interrupting the flow of the story (or, better yet, augmenting it), then go for it.

Don't bash the reader over the head with lore or miscellany tidbits. Give it relevance to the story you're telling in the moment.

Since I've looked into this...
If you're using Amazon as a publisher AND (this is important) only selling author copies, the per piece cost is about 7-8 usd for a 350-400pg 6"*9" softcover.
That kind of format (trade paperback) used to and still does run 12-15 usd.

The downside is: an editor, a typesetter, and artist. If you incorporate, you've got legal fees + taxes, no matter how small. And trust me, having done both small business quarterly tax returns and typeset a novel before, they are time sinks. I could typeset my book in about 7-10 days, but it's a very detail oriented job. Paying someone per piece? A quality job runs 2000+ usd.

The path forward is what snekguy is already doing, and I plan to as well.
Start small with self publishing, build the brand, and be relentless. I can and have done large bits of the backend. I have cover art that doesn't look like a bad FA submission.
It's just a matter of time.
